7676 /// Note that we are instantiating a default argument for a function
7677 /// parameter.
7678 InstantiatingTemplate(Sema &SemaRef, SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation,
7679 ParmVarDecl *Param,
7680 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> TemplateArgs,
7681 SourceRange InstantiationRange = SourceRange());
7682
7683 /// Note that we are substituting prior template arguments into a
7684 /// non-type parameter.
7685 InstantiatingTemplate(Sema &SemaRef, SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation,
7686 NamedDecl *Template,
7687 NonTypeTemplateParmDecl *Param,
7688 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> TemplateArgs,
7689 SourceRange InstantiationRange);
7690
7691 /// Note that we are substituting prior template arguments into a
7692 /// template template parameter.
7693 InstantiatingTemplate(Sema &SemaRef, SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation,
7694 NamedDecl *Template,
7695 TemplateTemplateParmDecl *Param,
7696 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> TemplateArgs,
7697 SourceRange InstantiationRange);
7698
7699 /// Note that we are checking the default template argument
7700 /// against the template parameter for a given template-id.
7701 InstantiatingTemplate(Sema &SemaRef, SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation,
7702 TemplateDecl *Template,
7703 NamedDecl *Param,
7704 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> TemplateArgs,
7705 SourceRange InstantiationRange);
7706
7707
7708 /// Note that we have finished instantiating this template.
7709 void Clear();
7710
7711 ~InstantiatingTemplate() { Clear(); }
7712
7713 /// Determines whether we have exceeded the maximum
7714 /// recursive template instantiations.
7715 bool isInvalid() const { return Invalid; }
7716
7717 /// Determine whether we are already instantiating this
7718 /// specialization in some surrounding active instantiation.
7719 bool isAlreadyInstantiating() const { return AlreadyInstantiating; }
7720
7721 private:
7722 Sema &SemaRef;
7723 bool Invalid;
7724 bool AlreadyInstantiating;
7725 bool CheckInstantiationDepth(SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation,
7726 SourceRange InstantiationRange);
7727
7728 InstantiatingTemplate(
7729 Sema &SemaRef, CodeSynthesisContext::SynthesisKind Kind,
7730 SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation, SourceRange InstantiationRange,
7731 Decl *Entity, NamedDecl *Template = nullptr,
7732 ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> TemplateArgs = None,
7733 sema::TemplateDeductionInfo *DeductionInfo = nullptr);
7734
7735 InstantiatingTemplate(const InstantiatingTemplate&) = delete;
7736
7737 InstantiatingTemplate&
7738 operator=(const InstantiatingTemplate&) = delete;
7739 };
7740
7741 void pushCodeSynthesisContext(CodeSynthesisContext Ctx);
7742 void popCodeSynthesisContext();
7743
7744 /// Determine whether we are currently performing template instantiation.
7745 bool inTemplateInstantiation() const {
7746 return CodeSynthesisContexts.size() > NonInstantiationEntries;
7747 }
7748
7749 void PrintContextStack() {
7750 if (!CodeSynthesisContexts.empty() &&
7751 CodeSynthesisContexts.size() != LastEmittedCodeSynthesisContextDepth) {
7752 PrintInstantiationStack();
7753 LastEmittedCodeSynthesisContextDepth = CodeSynthesisContexts.size();
7754 }
7755 if (PragmaAttributeCurrentTargetDecl)
7756 PrintPragmaAttributeInstantiationPoint();
7757 }
7758 void PrintInstantiationStack();
7759
7760 void PrintPragmaAttributeInstantiationPoint();
7761
7762 /// Determines whether we are currently in a context where
7763 /// template argument substitution failures are not considered
7764 /// errors.
7765 ///
7766 /// \returns An empty \c Optional if we're not in a SFINAE context.
7767 /// Otherwise, contains a pointer that, if non-NULL, contains the nearest
7768 /// template-deduction context object, which can be used to capture
7769 /// diagnostics that will be suppressed.
7770 Optional<sema::TemplateDeductionInfo *> isSFINAEContext() const;
7771
7772 /// Determines whether we are currently in a context that
7773 /// is not evaluated as per C++ [expr] p5.
7774 bool isUnevaluatedContext() const {
7775 assert(!ExprEvalContexts.empty() &&
7776 "Must be in an expression evaluation context");
7777 return ExprEvalContexts.back().isUnevaluated();
7778 }
7779
7780 /// RAII class used to determine whether SFINAE has
7781 /// trapped any errors that occur during template argument
7782 /// deduction.
7783 class SFINAETrap {
7784 Sema &SemaRef;
7785 unsigned PrevSFINAEErrors;
7786 bool PrevInNonInstantiationSFINAEContext;
7787 bool PrevAccessCheckingSFINAE;
7788 bool PrevLastDiagnosticIgnored;
7789
7790 public:
7791 explicit SFINAETrap(Sema &SemaRef, bool AccessCheckingSFINAE = false)
7792 : SemaRef(SemaRef), PrevSFINAEErrors(SemaRef.NumSFINAEErrors),
7793 PrevInNonInstantiationSFINAEContext(
7794 SemaRef.InNonInstantiationSFINAEContext),
7795 PrevAccessCheckingSFINAE(SemaRef.AccessCheckingSFINAE),
7796 PrevLastDiagnosticIgnored(
7797 SemaRef.getDiagnostics().isLastDiagnosticIgnored())
7798 {
7799 if (!SemaRef.isSFINAEContext())
7800 SemaRef.InNonInstantiationSFINAEContext = true;
7801 SemaRef.AccessCheckingSFINAE = AccessCheckingSFINAE;
7802 }
7803
7804 ~SFINAETrap() {
7805 SemaRef.NumSFINAEErrors = PrevSFINAEErrors;
7806 SemaRef.InNonInstantiationSFINAEContext
7807 = PrevInNonInstantiationSFINAEContext;
7808 SemaRef.AccessCheckingSFINAE = PrevAccessCheckingSFINAE;
7809 SemaRef.getDiagnostics().setLastDiagnosticIgnored(
7810 PrevLastDiagnosticIgnored);
7811 }
7812
7813 /// Determine whether any SFINAE errors have been trapped.
7814 bool hasErrorOccurred() const {
7815 return SemaRef.NumSFINAEErrors > PrevSFINAEErrors;
7816 }
7817 };
7818
7819 /// RAII class used to indicate that we are performing provisional
7820 /// semantic analysis to determine the validity of a construct, so
7821 /// typo-correction and diagnostics in the immediate context (not within
7822 /// implicitly-instantiated templates) should be suppressed.
7823 class TentativeAnalysisScope {
7824 Sema &SemaRef;
7825 // FIXME: Using a SFINAETrap for this is a hack.
7826 SFINAETrap Trap;
7827 bool PrevDisableTypoCorrection;
7828 public:
7829 explicit TentativeAnalysisScope(Sema &SemaRef)
7830 : SemaRef(SemaRef), Trap(SemaRef, true),
7831 PrevDisableTypoCorrection(SemaRef.DisableTypoCorrection) {
7832 SemaRef.DisableTypoCorrection = true;
7833 }
7834 ~TentativeAnalysisScope() {
7835 SemaRef.DisableTypoCorrection = PrevDisableTypoCorrection;
7836 }
7837 };
7838
7839 /// The current instantiation scope used to store local
7840 /// variables.
7841 LocalInstantiationScope *CurrentInstantiationScope;
7842
7843 /// Tracks whether we are in a context where typo correction is
7844 /// disabled.
7845 bool DisableTypoCorrection;
7846
7847 /// The number of typos corrected by CorrectTypo.
7848 unsigned TyposCorrected;
7849
7850 typedef llvm::SmallSet<SourceLocation, 2> SrcLocSet;
7851 typedef llvm::DenseMap<IdentifierInfo *, SrcLocSet> IdentifierSourceLocations;
7852
7853 /// A cache containing identifiers for which typo correction failed and
7854 /// their locations, so that repeated attempts to correct an identifier in a
7855 /// given location are ignored if typo correction already failed for it.
7856 IdentifierSourceLocations TypoCorrectionFailures;
7857
7858 /// Worker object for performing CFG-based warnings.
7859 sema::AnalysisBasedWarnings AnalysisWarnings;
7860 threadSafety::BeforeSet *ThreadSafetyDeclCache;
7861
7862 /// An entity for which implicit template instantiation is required.
7863 ///
7864 /// The source location associated with the declaration is the first place in
7865 /// the source code where the declaration was "used". It is not necessarily
7866 /// the point of instantiation (which will be either before or after the
7867 /// namespace-scope declaration that triggered this implicit instantiation),
7868 /// However, it is the location that diagnostics should generally refer to,
7869 /// because users will need to know what code triggered the instantiation.
7870 typedef std::pair<ValueDecl *, SourceLocation> PendingImplicitInstantiation;
7871
7872 /// The queue of implicit template instantiations that are required
7873 /// but have not yet been performed.
7874 std::deque<PendingImplicitInstantiation> PendingInstantiations;
7875
7876 /// Queue of implicit template instantiations that cannot be performed
7877 /// eagerly.
7878 SmallVector<PendingImplicitInstantiation, 1> LateParsedInstantiations;
7879
7880 class GlobalEagerInstantiationScope {
7881 public:
7882 GlobalEagerInstantiationScope(Sema &S, bool Enabled)
7883 : S(S), Enabled(Enabled) {
7884 if (!Enabled) return;
7885
7886 SavedPendingInstantiations.swap(S.PendingInstantiations);
7887 SavedVTableUses.swap(S.VTableUses);
7888 }
7889
7890 void perform() {
7891 if (Enabled) {
7892 S.DefineUsedVTables();
7893 S.PerformPendingInstantiations();
7894 }
7895 }
7896
7897 ~GlobalEagerInstantiationScope() {
7898 if (!Enabled) return;
7899
7900 // Restore the set of pending vtables.
7901 assert(S.VTableUses.empty() &&
7902 "VTableUses should be empty before it is discarded.");
7903 S.VTableUses.swap(SavedVTableUses);
7904
7905 // Restore the set of pending implicit instantiations.
7906 assert(S.PendingInstantiations.empty() &&
7907 "PendingInstantiations should be empty before it is discarded.");
7908 S.PendingInstantiations.swap(SavedPendingInstantiations);
7909 }
7910
7911 private:
7912 Sema &S;
7913 SmallVector<VTableUse, 16> SavedVTableUses;
7914 std::deque<PendingImplicitInstantiation> SavedPendingInstantiations;
7915 bool Enabled;
7916 };
7917
7918 /// The queue of implicit template instantiations that are required
7919 /// and must be performed within the current local scope.
7920 ///
7921 /// This queue is only used for member functions of local classes in
7922 /// templates, which must be instantiated in the same scope as their
7923 /// enclosing function, so that they can reference function-local
7924 /// types, static variables, enumerators, etc.
7925 std::deque<PendingImplicitInstantiation> PendingLocalImplicitInstantiations;
7926
7927 class LocalEagerInstantiationScope {
7928 public:
7929 LocalEagerInstantiationScope(Sema &S) : S(S) {
7930 SavedPendingLocalImplicitInstantiations.swap(
7931 S.PendingLocalImplicitInstantiations);
7932 }
7933
7934 void perform() { S.PerformPendingInstantiations(/*LocalOnly=*/true); }
7935
7936 ~LocalEagerInstantiationScope() {
7937 assert(S.PendingLocalImplicitInstantiations.empty() &&
7938 "there shouldn't be any pending local implicit instantiations");
7939 SavedPendingLocalImplicitInstantiations.swap(
7940 S.PendingLocalImplicitInstantiations);
7941 }
7942
7943 private:
7944 Sema &S;
7945 std::deque<PendingImplicitInstantiation>
7946 SavedPendingLocalImplicitInstantiations;
7947 };
7948
7949 /// A helper class for building up ExtParameterInfos.
7950 class ExtParameterInfoBuilder {
7951 SmallVector<FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo, 16> Infos;
7952 bool HasInteresting = false;
7953
7954 public:
7955 /// Set the ExtParameterInfo for the parameter at the given index,
7956 ///
7957 void set(unsigned index, FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo info) {
7958 assert(Infos.size() <= index);
7959 Infos.resize(index);
7960 Infos.push_back(info);
7961
7962 if (!HasInteresting)
7963 HasInteresting = (info != FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo());
7964 }
7965
7966 /// Return a pointer (suitable for setting in an ExtProtoInfo) to the
7967 /// ExtParameterInfo array we've built up.
7968 const FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo *
7969 getPointerOrNull(unsigned numParams) {
7970 if (!HasInteresting) return nullptr;
7971 Infos.resize(numParams);
7972 return Infos.data();
7973 }
7974 };

8895 /// extensions present in OpenCLDeclExtMap and if so return the
8896 /// extension(s) name(s).

8900 /// extensions present in OpenCLTypeExtMap and if so return the
8901 /// extension(s) name(s).

8905 template<typename T, typename MapT>
8906 std::string getOpenCLExtensionsFromExtMap(T* FT, MapT &Map);

8909 CurrOpenCLExtension = Ext;
8910 }

8913 /// OpenCL extensions are enabled. If \p Exts is empty, do nothing.

8919 /// nothing.

8922

8930 /// OpenCL extension is empty, do nothing.

8980 /// Checks if a type or a declaration is disabled due to the owning extension
8981 /// being disabled, and emits diagnostic messages if it is disabled.
8982 /// \param D type or declaration to be checked.
8983 /// \param DiagLoc source location for the diagnostic message.
8984 /// \param DiagInfo information to be emitted for the diagnostic message.
8985 /// \param SrcRange source range of the declaration.
8986 /// \param Map maps type or declaration to the extensions.
8987 /// \param Selector selects diagnostic message: 0 for type and 1 for
8988 /// declaration.
8989 /// \return true if the type or declaration is disabled.
8990 template <typename T, typename DiagLocT, typename DiagInfoT, typename MapT>
8991 bool checkOpenCLDisabledTypeOrDecl(T D, DiagLocT DiagLoc, DiagInfoT DiagInfo,
8992 MapT &Map, unsigned Selector = 0,
8993 SourceRange SrcRange = SourceRange());

9136 /// diagnosed if OpenMP (offloading) is enabled.
9137 bool shouldDiagnoseTargetSupportFromOpenMP() const {
9138 return !getLangOpts().OpenMPIsDevice || isInOpenMPDeclareTargetContext() ||
9139 isInOpenMPTargetExecutionDirective();

9704 /// The kind of conversion being performed.
9705 enum CheckedConversionKind {
9706 /// An implicit conversion.
9707 CCK_ImplicitConversion,
9708 /// A C-style cast.
9709 CCK_CStyleCast,
9710 /// A functional-style cast.
9711 CCK_FunctionalCast,
9712 /// A cast other than a C-style cast.
9713 CCK_OtherCast,
9714 /// A conversion for an operand of a builtin overloaded operator.
9715 CCK_ForBuiltinOverloadedOp
9716 };
9717
9718 static bool isCast(CheckedConversionKind CCK) {
9719 return CCK == CCK_CStyleCast || CCK == CCK_FunctionalCast ||
9720 CCK == CCK_OtherCast;
9721 }
9722
9723 /// ImpCastExprToType - If Expr is not of type 'Type', insert an implicit
9724 /// cast. If there is already an implicit cast, merge into the existing one.
9725 /// If isLvalue, the result of the cast is an lvalue.
9726 ExprResult ImpCastExprToType(Expr *E, QualType Type, CastKind CK,
9727 ExprValueKind VK = VK_RValue,
9728 const CXXCastPath *BasePath = nullptr,
9729 CheckedConversionKind CCK
9730 = CCK_ImplicitConversion);
9731
9732 /// ImpCastPointerToCHERICapability - Checks if pointer type FromTy can be implicitly converted to
9733 /// capability type ToTy
9734 bool ImpCastPointerToCHERICapability(QualType FromTy, QualType ToTy, Expr *&From, bool Diagnose = true);
9735
9736 /// ScalarTypeToBooleanCastKind - Returns the cast kind corresponding
9737 /// to the conversion from scalar type ScalarTy to the Boolean type.
9738 static CastKind ScalarTypeToBooleanCastKind(QualType ScalarTy);
9739
9740 /// IgnoredValueConversions - Given that an expression's result is
9741 /// syntactically ignored, perform any conversions that are
9742 /// required.
9743 ExprResult IgnoredValueConversions(Expr *E);
9744
9745 // UsualUnaryConversions - promotes integers (C99 6.3.1.1p2) and converts
9746 // functions and arrays to their respective pointers (C99 6.3.2.1).
9747 ExprResult UsualUnaryConversions(Expr *E);
9748
9749 /// CallExprUnaryConversions - a special case of an unary conversion
9750 /// performed on a function designator of a call expression.
9751 ExprResult CallExprUnaryConversions(Expr *E);
9752
9753 // DefaultFunctionArrayConversion - converts functions and arrays
9754 // to their respective pointers (C99 6.3.2.1).
9755 ExprResult DefaultFunctionArrayConversion(Expr *E, bool Diagnose = true);
9756
9757 // DefaultFunctionArrayLvalueConversion - converts functions and
9758 // arrays to their respective pointers and performs the
9759 // lvalue-to-rvalue conversion.
9760 ExprResult DefaultFunctionArrayLvalueConversion(Expr *E,
9761 bool Diagnose = true);
9762
9763 // DefaultLvalueConversion - performs lvalue-to-rvalue conversion on
9764 // the operand. This is DefaultFunctionArrayLvalueConversion,
9765 // except that it assumes the operand isn't of function or array
9766 // type.
9767 ExprResult DefaultLvalueConversion(Expr *E);
9768
9769 // DefaultArgumentPromotion (C99 6.5.2.2p6). Used for function calls that
9770 // do not have a prototype. Integer promotions are performed on each
9771 // argument, and arguments that have type float are promoted to double.
9772 ExprResult DefaultArgumentPromotion(Expr *E);
9773
9774 /// If \p E is a prvalue denoting an unmaterialized temporary, materialize
9775 /// it as an xvalue. In C++98, the result will still be a prvalue, because
9776 /// we don't have xvalues there.
9777 ExprResult TemporaryMaterializationConversion(Expr *E);

9827 // UsualArithmeticConversions - performs the UsualUnaryConversions on it's
9828 // operands and then handles various conversions that are common to binary
9829 // operators (C99 6.3.1.8). If both operands aren't arithmetic, this
9830 // routine returns the first non-arithmetic type found. The client is
9831 // responsible for emitting appropriate error diagnostics.
9832 QualType UsualArithmeticConversions(ExprResult &LHS, ExprResult &RHS,
9833 bool IsCompAssign = false);

9835 /// AssignConvertType - All of the 'assignment' semantic checks return this
9836 /// enum to indicate whether the assignment was allowed. These checks are
9837 /// done for simple assignments, as well as initialization, return from
9838 /// function, argument passing, etc. The query is phrased in terms of a
9839 /// source and destination type.
9840 enum AssignConvertType {
9841 /// Compatible - the types are compatible according to the standard.
9842 Compatible,
9843
9844 /// PointerToInt - The assignment converts a pointer to an int, which we
9845 /// accept as an extension.
9846 PointerToInt,
9847
9848 /// IntToPointer - The assignment converts an int to a pointer, which we
9849 /// accept as an extension.
9850 IntToPointer,
9851
9852 /// CHERICapabilityToPointer - The assignment converts a capability to a
9853 /// pointer, which we reject (it needs an explicit __cheri_fromcap).
9854 CHERICapabilityToPointer,
9855 /// PointerToCHERICapability - The assignment converts a pointer to a
9856 /// capability, which we reject (it needs an explicit __cheri_tocap).
9857 PointerToCHERICapability,
9858
9859 /// FunctionVoidPointer - The assignment is between a function pointer and
9860 /// void*, which the standard doesn't allow, but we accept as an extension.
9861 FunctionVoidPointer,
9862
9863 /// IncompatiblePointer - The assignment is between two pointers types that
9864 /// are not compatible, but we accept them as an extension.
9865 IncompatiblePointer,
9866
9867 /// IncompatiblePointerSign - The assignment is between two pointers types
9868 /// which point to integers which have a different sign, but are otherwise
9869 /// identical. This is a subset of the above, but broken out because it's by
9870 /// far the most common case of incompatible pointers.
9871 IncompatiblePointerSign,
9872
9873 /// CompatiblePointerDiscardsQualifiers - The assignment discards
9874 /// c/v/r qualifiers, which we accept as an extension.
9875 CompatiblePointerDiscardsQualifiers,
9876
9877 /// IncompatiblePointerDiscardsQualifiers - The assignment
9878 /// discards qualifiers that we don't permit to be discarded,
9879 /// like address spaces.
9880 IncompatiblePointerDiscardsQualifiers,
9881
9882 /// IncompatibleNestedPointerAddressSpaceMismatch - The assignment
9883 /// changes address spaces in nested pointer types which is not allowed.
9884 /// For instance, converting __private int ** to __generic int ** is
9885 /// illegal even though __private could be converted to __generic.
9886 IncompatibleNestedPointerAddressSpaceMismatch,
9887
9888 /// IncompatibleNestedPointerQualifiers - The assignment is between two
9889 /// nested pointer types, and the qualifiers other than the first two
9890 /// levels differ e.g. char ** -> const char **, but we accept them as an
9891 /// extension.
9892 IncompatibleNestedPointerQualifiers,
9893
9894 /// IncompatibleVectors - The assignment is between two vector types that
9895 /// have the same size, which we accept as an extension.
9896 IncompatibleVectors,
9897
9898 /// IntToBlockPointer - The assignment converts an int to a block
9899 /// pointer. We disallow this.
9900 IntToBlockPointer,
9901
9902 /// IncompatibleBlockPointer - The assignment is between two block
9903 /// pointers types that are not compatible.
9904 IncompatibleBlockPointer,
9905
9906 /// IncompatibleObjCQualifiedId - The assignment is between a qualified
9907 /// id type and something else (that is incompatible with it). For example,
9908 /// "id <XXX>" = "Foo *", where "Foo *" doesn't implement the XXX protocol.
9909 IncompatibleObjCQualifiedId,
9910
9911 /// IncompatibleObjCWeakRef - Assigning a weak-unavailable object to an
9912 /// object with __weak qualifier.
9913 IncompatibleObjCWeakRef,
9914
9915 /// Incompatible - We reject this conversion outright, it is invalid to
9916 /// represent it in the AST.
9917 Incompatible
9918 };
9919
9920 /// DiagnoseAssignmentResult - Emit a diagnostic, if required, for the
9921 /// assignment conversion type specified by ConvTy. This returns true if the
9922 /// conversion was invalid or false if the conversion was accepted.
9923 bool DiagnoseAssignmentResult(AssignConvertType ConvTy,
9924 SourceLocation Loc,
9925 QualType DstType, QualType SrcType,
9926 Expr *SrcExpr, AssignmentAction Action,
9927 bool *Complained = nullptr);

9955 /// Check assignment constraints for an assignment of RHS to LHSType.
9956 ///
9957 /// \param LHSType The destination type for the assignment.
9958 /// \param RHS The source expression for the assignment.
9959 /// \param Diagnose If \c true, diagnostics may be produced when checking
9960 /// for assignability. If a diagnostic is produced, \p RHS will be
9961 /// set to ExprError(). Note that this function may still return
9962 /// without producing a diagnostic, even for an invalid assignment.
9963 /// \param DiagnoseCFAudited If \c true, the target is a function parameter
9964 /// in an audited Core Foundation API and does not need to be checked
9965 /// for ARC retain issues.
9966 /// \param ConvertRHS If \c true, \p RHS will be updated to model the
9967 /// conversions necessary to perform the assignment. If \c false,
9968 /// \p Diagnose must also be \c false.

9971 bool DiagnoseCFAudited = false, bool ConvertRHS = true);

10218 class ConditionResult {
10219 Decl *ConditionVar;
10220 FullExprArg Condition;
10221 bool Invalid;
10222 bool HasKnownValue;
10223 bool KnownValue;
10224
10225 friend class Sema;
10226 ConditionResult(Sema &S, Decl *ConditionVar, FullExprArg Condition,
10227 bool IsConstexpr)
10228 : ConditionVar(ConditionVar), Condition(Condition), Invalid(false),
10229 HasKnownValue(IsConstexpr && Condition.get() &&
10230 !Condition.get()->isValueDependent()),
10231 KnownValue(HasKnownValue &&
10232 !!Condition.get()->EvaluateKnownConstInt(S.Context)) {}
10233 explicit ConditionResult(bool Invalid)
10234 : ConditionVar(nullptr), Condition(nullptr), Invalid(Invalid),
10235 HasKnownValue(false), KnownValue(false) {}
10236
10237 public:
10238 ConditionResult() : ConditionResult(false) {}
10239 bool isInvalid() const { return Invalid; }
10240 std::pair<VarDecl *, Expr *> get() const {
10241 return std::make_pair(cast_or_null<VarDecl>(ConditionVar),
10242 Condition.get());
10243 }
10244 llvm::Optional<bool> getKnownValue() const {
10245 if (!HasKnownValue)
10246 return None;
10247 return KnownValue;
10248 }
10249 };
10250 static ConditionResult ConditionError() { return ConditionResult(true); }

10347private:
10348 unsigned ForceCUDAHostDeviceDepth = 0;
10349
10350public:
10351 /// Increments our count of the number of times we've seen a pragma forcing
10352 /// functions to be __host__ __device__. So long as this count is greater
10353 /// than zero, all functions encountered will be __host__ __device__.
10354 void PushForceCUDAHostDevice();
10355
10356 /// Decrements our count of the number of times we've seen a pragma forcing
10357 /// functions to be __host__ __device__. Returns false if the count is 0
10358 /// before incrementing, so you can emit an error.
10359 bool PopForceCUDAHostDevice();
10360
10361 /// Diagnostics that are emitted only if we discover that the given function
10362 /// must be codegen'ed. Because handling these correctly adds overhead to
10363 /// compilation, this is currently only enabled for CUDA compilations.
10364 llvm::DenseMap<CanonicalDeclPtr<FunctionDecl>,
10365 std::vector<PartialDiagnosticAt>>
10366 DeviceDeferredDiags;
10367
10368 /// A pair of a canonical FunctionDecl and a SourceLocation. When used as the
10369 /// key in a hashtable, both the FD and location are hashed.
10370 struct FunctionDeclAndLoc {
10371 CanonicalDeclPtr<FunctionDecl> FD;
10372 SourceLocation Loc;
10373 };
10374
10375 /// FunctionDecls and SourceLocations for which CheckCUDACall has emitted a
10376 /// (maybe deferred) "bad call" diagnostic. We use this to avoid emitting the
10377 /// same deferred diag twice.
10378 llvm::DenseSet<FunctionDeclAndLoc> LocsWithCUDACallDiags;
10379
10380 /// An inverse call graph, mapping known-emitted functions to one of their
10381 /// known-emitted callers (plus the location of the call).
10382 ///
10383 /// Functions that we can tell a priori must be emitted aren't added to this
10384 /// map.
10385 llvm::DenseMap</* Callee = */ CanonicalDeclPtr<FunctionDecl>,
10386 /* Caller = */ FunctionDeclAndLoc>
10387 DeviceKnownEmittedFns;
10388
10389 /// A partial call graph maintained during CUDA/OpenMP device code compilation
10390 /// to support deferred diagnostics.
10391 ///
10392 /// Functions are only added here if, at the time they're considered, they are
10393 /// not known-emitted. As soon as we discover that a function is
10394 /// known-emitted, we remove it and everything it transitively calls from this
10395 /// set and add those functions to DeviceKnownEmittedFns.
10396 llvm::DenseMap</* Caller = */ CanonicalDeclPtr<FunctionDecl>,
10397 /* Callees = */ llvm::MapVector<CanonicalDeclPtr<FunctionDecl>,
10398 SourceLocation>>
10399 DeviceCallGraph;
10400
10401 /// Diagnostic builder for CUDA/OpenMP devices errors which may or may not be
10402 /// deferred.
10403 ///
10404 /// In CUDA, there exist constructs (e.g. variable-length arrays, try/catch)
10405 /// which are not allowed to appear inside __device__ functions and are
10406 /// allowed to appear in __host__ __device__ functions only if the host+device
10407 /// function is never codegen'ed.
10408 ///
10409 /// To handle this, we use the notion of "deferred diagnostics", where we
10410 /// attach a diagnostic to a FunctionDecl that's emitted iff it's codegen'ed.
10411 ///
10412 /// This class lets you emit either a regular diagnostic, a deferred
10413 /// diagnostic, or no diagnostic at all, according to an argument you pass to
10414 /// its constructor, thus simplifying the process of creating these "maybe
10415 /// deferred" diagnostics.
10416 class DeviceDiagBuilder {
10417 public:
10418 enum Kind {
10419 /// Emit no diagnostics.
10420 K_Nop,
10421 /// Emit the diagnostic immediately (i.e., behave like Sema::Diag()).
10422 K_Immediate,
10423 /// Emit the diagnostic immediately, and, if it's a warning or error, also
10424 /// emit a call stack showing how this function can be reached by an a
10425 /// priori known-emitted function.
10426 K_ImmediateWithCallStack,
10427 /// Create a deferred diagnostic, which is emitted only if the function
10428 /// it's attached to is codegen'ed. Also emit a call stack as with
10429 /// K_ImmediateWithCallStack.
10430 K_Deferred
10431 };
10432
10433 DeviceDiagBuilder(Kind K, SourceLocation Loc, unsigned DiagID,
10434 FunctionDecl *Fn, Sema &S);
10435 DeviceDiagBuilder(DeviceDiagBuilder &&D);
10436 DeviceDiagBuilder(const DeviceDiagBuilder &) = default;
10437 ~DeviceDiagBuilder();
10438
10439 /// Convertible to bool: True if we immediately emitted an error, false if
10440 /// we didn't emit an error or we created a deferred error.
10441 ///
10442 /// Example usage:
10443 ///
10444 /// if (DeviceDiagBuilder(...) << foo << bar)
10445 /// return ExprError();
10446 ///
10447 /// But see CUDADiagIfDeviceCode() and CUDADiagIfHostCode() -- you probably
10448 /// want to use these instead of creating a DeviceDiagBuilder yourself.
10449 operator bool() const { return ImmediateDiag.hasValue(); }
10450
10451 template <typename T>
10452 friend const DeviceDiagBuilder &operator<<(const DeviceDiagBuilder &Diag,
10453 const T &Value) {
10454 if (Diag.ImmediateDiag.hasValue())
10455 *Diag.ImmediateDiag << Value;
10456 else if (Diag.PartialDiagId.hasValue())
10457 Diag.S.DeviceDeferredDiags[Diag.Fn][*Diag.PartialDiagId].second
10458 << Value;
10459 return Diag;
10460 }
10461
10462 private:
10463 Sema &S;
10464 SourceLocation Loc;
10465 unsigned DiagID;
10466 FunctionDecl *Fn;
10467 bool ShowCallStack;
10468
10469 // Invariant: At most one of these Optionals has a value.
10470 // FIXME: Switch these to a Variant once that exists.
10471 llvm::Optional<SemaDiagnosticBuilder> ImmediateDiag;
10472 llvm::Optional<unsigned> PartialDiagId;
10473 };

10475 /// Indicate that this function (and thus everything it transtively calls)
10476 /// will be codegen'ed, and emit any deferred diagnostics on this function and
10477 /// its (transitive) callees.
10478 void markKnownEmitted(
10479 Sema &S, FunctionDecl *OrigCaller, FunctionDecl *OrigCallee,
10480 SourceLocation OrigLoc,
10481 const llvm::function_ref<bool(Sema &, FunctionDecl *)> IsKnownEmitted);

10483 /// Creates a DeviceDiagBuilder that emits the diagnostic if the current context
10484 /// is "used as device code".
10485 ///
10486 /// - If CurContext is a __host__ function, does not emit any diagnostics.
10487 /// - If CurContext is a __device__ or __global__ function, emits the
10488 /// diagnostics immediately.
10489 /// - If CurContext is a __host__ __device__ function and we are compiling for
10490 /// the device, creates a diagnostic which is emitted if and when we realize
10491 /// that the function will be codegen'ed.
10492 ///
10493 /// Example usage:
10494 ///
10495 /// // Variable-length arrays are not allowed in CUDA device code.
10496 /// if (CUDADiagIfDeviceCode(Loc, diag::err_cuda_vla) << CurrentCUDATarget())
10497 /// return ExprError();
10498 /// // Otherwise, continue parsing as normal.
10499 DeviceDiagBuilder CUDADiagIfDeviceCode(SourceLocation Loc, unsigned DiagID);
10500
10501 /// Creates a DeviceDiagBuilder that emits the diagnostic if the current context
10502 /// is "used as host code".
10503 ///
10504 /// Same as CUDADiagIfDeviceCode, with "host" and "device" switched.
10505 DeviceDiagBuilder CUDADiagIfHostCode(SourceLocation Loc, unsigned DiagID);
10506
10507 /// Creates a DeviceDiagBuilder that emits the diagnostic if the current
10508 /// context is "used as device code".
10509 ///
10510 /// - If CurContext is a `declare target` function or it is known that the
10511 /// function is emitted for the device, emits the diagnostics immediately.
10512 /// - If CurContext is a non-`declare target` function and we are compiling
10513 /// for the device, creates a diagnostic which is emitted if and when we
10514 /// realize that the function will be codegen'ed.
10515 ///
10516 /// Example usage:
10517 ///
10518 /// // Variable-length arrays are not allowed in NVPTX device code.
10519 /// if (diagIfOpenMPDeviceCode(Loc, diag::err_vla_unsupported))
10520 /// return ExprError();
10521 /// // Otherwise, continue parsing as normal.
10522 DeviceDiagBuilder diagIfOpenMPDeviceCode(SourceLocation Loc, unsigned DiagID);
10523
10524 DeviceDiagBuilder targetDiag(SourceLocation Loc, unsigned DiagID);

10534 /// Determines whether the given function is a CUDA device/host/kernel/etc.

10538 /// will get it wrong. Returns CFT_Host if D is null.

10548 // CUDA function call preference. Must be ordered numerically from
10549 // worst to best.
10550 enum CUDAFunctionPreference {
10551 CFP_Never, // Invalid caller/callee combination.
10552 CFP_WrongSide, // Calls from host-device to host or device
10553 // function that do not match current compilation
10554 // mode.
10555 CFP_HostDevice, // Any calls to host/device functions.
10556 CFP_SameSide, // Calls from host-device to host or device
10557 // function matching current compilation mode.
10558 CFP_Native, // host-to-host or device-to-device calls.
10559 };
10560
10561 /// Identifies relative preference of a given Caller/Callee
10562 /// combination, based on their host/device attributes.
10563 /// \param Caller function which needs address of \p Callee.
10564 /// nullptr in case of global context.
10565 /// \param Callee target function
10566 ///
10567 /// \returns preference value for particular Caller/Callee combination.
10568 CUDAFunctionPreference IdentifyCUDAPreference(const FunctionDecl *Caller,
10569 const FunctionDecl *Callee);
10570
10571 /// Determines whether Caller may invoke Callee, based on their CUDA
10572 /// host/device attributes. Returns false if the call is not allowed.
10573 ///
10574 /// Note: Will return true for CFP_WrongSide calls. These may appear in
10575 /// semantically correct CUDA programs, but only if they're never codegen'ed.
10576 bool IsAllowedCUDACall(const FunctionDecl *Caller,
10577 const FunctionDecl *Callee) {
10578 return IdentifyCUDAPreference(Caller, Callee) != CFP_Never;
10579 }

10581 /// May add implicit CUDAHostAttr and CUDADeviceAttr attributes to FD,
10582 /// depending on FD and the current compilation settings.
10583 void maybeAddCUDAHostDeviceAttrs(FunctionDecl *FD,
10584 const LookupResult &Previous);
10585
10586public:
10587 /// Check whether we're allowed to call Callee from the current context.
10588 ///
10589 /// - If the call is never allowed in a semantically-correct program
10590 /// (CFP_Never), emits an error and returns false.
10591 ///
10592 /// - If the call is allowed in semantically-correct programs, but only if
10593 /// it's never codegen'ed (CFP_WrongSide), creates a deferred diagnostic to
10594 /// be emitted if and when the caller is codegen'ed, and returns true.
10595 ///
10596 /// Will only create deferred diagnostics for a given SourceLocation once,
10597 /// so you can safely call this multiple times without generating duplicate
10598 /// deferred errors.
10599 ///
10600 /// - Otherwise, returns true without emitting any diagnostics.
10601 bool CheckCUDACall(SourceLocation Loc, FunctionDecl *Callee);
10602
10603 /// Set __device__ or __host__ __device__ attributes on the given lambda
10604 /// operator() method.
10605 ///
10606 /// CUDA lambdas declared inside __device__ or __global__ functions inherit
10607 /// the __device__ attribute. Similarly, lambdas inside __host__ __device__
10608 /// functions become __host__ __device__ themselves.
10609 void CUDASetLambdaAttrs(CXXMethodDecl *Method);

10612 /// from \p Caller context and erases all functions with lower

10616 SmallVectorImpl<std::pair<DeclAccessPair, FunctionDecl *>> &Matches);

10618 /// Given a implicit special member, infer its CUDA target from the
10619 /// calls it needs to make to underlying base/field special members.
10620 /// \param ClassDecl the class for which the member is being created.
10621 /// \param CSM the kind of special member.
10622 /// \param MemberDecl the special member itself.
10623 /// \param ConstRHS true if this is a copy operation with a const object on
10624 /// its RHS.
10625 /// \param Diagnose true if this call should emit diagnostics.
10626 /// \return true if there was an error inferring.
10627 /// The result of this call is implicit CUDA target attribute(s) attached to
10628 /// the member declaration.

10640 // \brief Checks that initializers of \p Var satisfy CUDA restrictions. In
10641 // case of error emits appropriate diagnostic and invalidates \p Var.
10642 //
10643 // \details CUDA allows only empty constructors as initializers for global
10644 // variables (see E.2.3.1, CUDA 7.5). The same restriction also applies to all
10645 // __shared__ variables whether they are local or not (they all are implicitly
10646 // static in CUDA). One exception is that CUDA allows constant initializers
10647 // for __constant__ and __device__ variables.

10662 /// \name Code completion
10663 //@{
10664 /// Describes the context in which code completion occurs.
10665 enum ParserCompletionContext {
10666 /// Code completion occurs at top-level or namespace context.
10667 PCC_Namespace,
10668 /// Code completion occurs within a class, struct, or union.
10669 PCC_Class,
10670 /// Code completion occurs within an Objective-C interface, protocol,
10671 /// or category.
10672 PCC_ObjCInterface,
10673 /// Code completion occurs within an Objective-C implementation or
10674 /// category implementation
10675 PCC_ObjCImplementation,
10676 /// Code completion occurs within the list of instance variables
10677 /// in an Objective-C interface, protocol, category, or implementation.
10678 PCC_ObjCInstanceVariableList,
10679 /// Code completion occurs following one or more template
10680 /// headers.
10681 PCC_Template,
10682 /// Code completion occurs following one or more template
10683 /// headers within a class.
10684 PCC_MemberTemplate,
10685 /// Code completion occurs within an expression.
10686 PCC_Expression,
10687 /// Code completion occurs within a statement, which may
10688 /// also be an expression or a declaration.
10689 PCC_Statement,
10690 /// Code completion occurs at the beginning of the
10691 /// initialization statement (or expression) in a for loop.
10692 PCC_ForInit,
10693 /// Code completion occurs within the condition of an if,
10694 /// while, switch, or for statement.
10695 PCC_Condition,
10696 /// Code completion occurs within the body of a function on a
10697 /// recovery path, where we do not have a specific handle on our position
10698 /// in the grammar.
10699 PCC_RecoveryInFunction,
10700 /// Code completion occurs where only a type is permitted.
10701 PCC_Type,
10702 /// Code completion occurs in a parenthesized expression, which
10703 /// might also be a type cast.
10704 PCC_ParenthesizedExpression,
10705 /// Code completion occurs within a sequence of declaration
10706 /// specifiers within a function, method, or block.
10707 PCC_LocalDeclarationSpecifiers
10708 };

11099 /// Retrieve the parser's current scope.
11100 ///
11101 /// This routine must only be used when it is certain that semantic analysis
11102 /// and the parser are in precisely the same context, which is not the case
11103 /// when, e.g., we are performing any kind of template instantiation.
11104 /// Therefore, the only safe places to use this scope are in the parser
11105 /// itself and in routines directly invoked from the parser and *never* from
11106 /// template substitution or instantiation.

11122 const DeclContext *getCurObjCLexicalContext() const {
11123 const DeclContext *DC = getCurLexicalContext();
11124 // A category implicitly has the attribute of the interface.

11126 DC = CatD->getClassInterface();

11130 /// To be used for checking whether the arguments being passed to
11131 /// function exceeds the number of parameters expected for it.
11132 static bool TooManyArguments(size_t NumParams, size_t NumArgs,
11133 bool PartialOverloading = false) {
11134 // We check whether we're just after a comma in code-completion.
11135 if (NumArgs > 0 && PartialOverloading)
11136 return NumArgs + 1 > NumParams; // If so, we view as an extra argument.
11137 return NumArgs > NumParams;
11138 }

11140 // Emitting members of dllexported classes is delayed until the class
11141 // (including field initializers) is fully parsed.
11142 SmallVector<CXXRecordDecl*, 4> DelayedDllExportClasses;
11143
11144private:
11145 class SavePendingParsedClassStateRAII {
11146 public:
11147 SavePendingParsedClassStateRAII(Sema &S) : S(S) { swapSavedState(); }
11148
11149 ~SavePendingParsedClassStateRAII() {
11150 assert(S.DelayedOverridingExceptionSpecChecks.empty() &&
11151 "there shouldn't be any pending delayed exception spec checks");
11152 assert(S.DelayedEquivalentExceptionSpecChecks.empty() &&
11153 "there shouldn't be any pending delayed exception spec checks");
11154 assert(S.DelayedDllExportClasses.empty() &&
11155 "there shouldn't be any pending delayed DLL export classes");
11156 swapSavedState();
11157 }
11158
11159 private:
11160 Sema &S;
11161 decltype(DelayedOverridingExceptionSpecChecks)
11162 SavedOverridingExceptionSpecChecks;
11163 decltype(DelayedEquivalentExceptionSpecChecks)
11164 SavedEquivalentExceptionSpecChecks;
11165 decltype(DelayedDllExportClasses) SavedDllExportClasses;
11166
11167 void swapSavedState() {
11168 SavedOverridingExceptionSpecChecks.swap(
11169 S.DelayedOverridingExceptionSpecChecks);
11170 SavedEquivalentExceptionSpecChecks.swap(
11171 S.DelayedEquivalentExceptionSpecChecks);
11172 SavedDllExportClasses.swap(S.DelayedDllExportClasses);
11173 }
11174 };
11175
11176 /// Helper class that collects misaligned member designations and
11177 /// their location info for delayed diagnostics.
11178 struct MisalignedMember {
11179 Expr *E;
11180 RecordDecl *RD;
11181 ValueDecl *MD;
11182 CharUnits Alignment;
11183
11184 MisalignedMember() : E(), RD(), MD(), Alignment() {}
11185 MisalignedMember(Expr *E, RecordDecl *RD, ValueDecl *MD,
11186 CharUnits Alignment)
11187 : E(E), RD(RD), MD(MD), Alignment(Alignment) {}
11188 explicit MisalignedMember(Expr *E)
11189 : MisalignedMember(E, nullptr, nullptr, CharUnits()) {}
11190
11191 bool operator==(const MisalignedMember &m) { return this->E == m.E; }
11192 };
11193 /// Small set of gathered accesses to potentially misaligned members
11194 /// due to the packed attribute.
11195 SmallVector<MisalignedMember, 4> MisalignedMembers;
11196
11197 /// Adds an expression to the set of gathered misaligned members.
11198 void AddPotentialMisalignedMembers(Expr *E, RecordDecl *RD, ValueDecl *MD,
11199 CharUnits Alignment);
11200
11201public:
11202 /// Diagnoses the current set of gathered accesses. This typically
11203 /// happens at full expression level. The set is cleared after emitting the
11204 /// diagnostics.
11205 void DiagnoseMisalignedMembers();
11206
11207 /// This function checks if the expression is in the sef of potentially
11208 /// misaligned members and it is converted to some pointer type T with lower
11209 /// or equal alignment requirements. If so it removes it. This is used when
11210 /// we do not want to diagnose such misaligned access (e.g. in conversions to
11211 /// void*).
11212 void DiscardMisalignedMemberAddress(const Type *T, Expr *E);
11213
11214 /// This function calls Action when it determines that E designates a
11215 /// misaligned member due to the packed attribute. This is used to emit
11216 /// local diagnostics like in reference binding.
11217 void RefersToMemberWithReducedAlignment(
11218 Expr *E,
11219 llvm::function_ref<void(Expr *, RecordDecl *, FieldDecl *, CharUnits)>
11220 Action);

11222 /// Describes the reason a calling convention specification was ignored, used
11223 /// for diagnostics.
11224 enum class CallingConventionIgnoredReason {
11225 ForThisTarget = 0,
11226 VariadicFunction,
11227 ConstructorDestructor,
11228 BuiltinFunction
11229 };
11230};

11232/// RAII object that enters a new expression evaluation context.
11233class EnterExpressionEvaluationContext {
11234 Sema &Actions;
11235 bool Entered = true;
11236
11237public:
11238 EnterExpressionEvaluationContext(
11239 Sema &Actions, Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext NewContext,
11240 Decl *LambdaContextDecl = nullptr,
11241 Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContextRecord::ExpressionKind ExprContext =
11242 Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContextRecord::EK_Other,
11243 bool ShouldEnter = true)
11244 : Actions(Actions), Entered(ShouldEnter) {
11245 if (Entered)
11246 Actions.PushExpressionEvaluationContext(NewContext, LambdaContextDecl,
11247 ExprContext);
11248 }
11249 EnterExpressionEvaluationContext(
11250 Sema &Actions, Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext NewContext,
11251 Sema::ReuseLambdaContextDecl_t,
11252 Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContextRecord::ExpressionKind ExprContext =
11253 Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContextRecord::EK_Other)
11254 : Actions(Actions) {
11255 Actions.PushExpressionEvaluationContext(
11256 NewContext, Sema::ReuseLambdaContextDecl, ExprContext);
11257 }
11258
11259 enum InitListTag { InitList };
11260 EnterExpressionEvaluationContext(Sema &Actions, InitListTag,
11261 bool ShouldEnter = true)
11262 : Actions(Actions), Entered(false) {
11263 // In C++11 onwards, narrowing checks are performed on the contents of
11264 // braced-init-lists, even when they occur within unevaluated operands.
11265 // Therefore we still need to instantiate constexpr functions used in such
11266 // a context.
11267 if (ShouldEnter && Actions.isUnevaluatedContext() &&
11268 Actions.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11) {
11269 Actions.PushExpressionEvaluationContext(
11270 Sema::ExpressionEvaluationContext::UnevaluatedList);
11271 Entered = true;
11272 }
11273 }
11274
11275 ~EnterExpressionEvaluationContext() {
11276 if (Entered)
11277 Actions.PopExpressionEvaluationContext();
11278 }
11279};

11281DeductionFailureInfo
11282MakeDeductionFailureInfo(ASTContext &Context, Sema::TemplateDeductionResult TDK,
11283 sema::TemplateDeductionInfo &Info);

11285/// Contains a late templated function.
11286/// Will be parsed at the end of the translation unit, used by Sema & Parser.
11287struct LateParsedTemplate {
11288 CachedTokens Toks;
11289 /// The template function declaration to be late parsed.
11290 Decl *D;
11291};

11294namespace llvm {
11295// Hash a FunctionDeclAndLoc by looking at both its FunctionDecl and its
11296// SourceLocation.
11297template <> struct DenseMapInfo<clang::Sema::FunctionDeclAndLoc> {
11298 using FunctionDeclAndLoc = clang::Sema::FunctionDeclAndLoc;
11299 using FDBaseInfo = DenseMapInfo<clang::CanonicalDeclPtr<clang::FunctionDecl>>;
11300
11301 static FunctionDeclAndLoc getEmptyKey() {
11302 return {FDBaseInfo::getEmptyKey(), clang::SourceLocation()};
11303 }
11304
11305 static FunctionDeclAndLoc getTombstoneKey() {
11306 return {FDBaseInfo::getTombstoneKey(), clang::SourceLocation()};
11307 }
11308
11309 static unsigned getHashValue(const FunctionDeclAndLoc &FDL) {
11310 return hash_combine(FDBaseInfo::getHashValue(FDL.FD),
11311 FDL.Loc.getRawEncoding());
11312 }
11313
11314 static bool isEqual(const FunctionDeclAndLoc &LHS,
11315 const FunctionDeclAndLoc &RHS) {
11316 return LHS.FD == RHS.FD && LHS.Loc == RHS.Loc;
11317 }
11318};
11319} // namespace llvm
